President Muhammadu Buhari yesterday assented to a bill, ‘Mutual Assistance in Criminal Matters Act, 2019’ for the recovery of crime proceeds abroad. The law, according to the presidential aide on National Assembly (Senate), Senator Ita Enang,  took effect from June 20. He said the law seeks to facilitate the identification, tracing, freezing, restraining, recovery, forfeiture and confiscation of proceeds, property and other instruments of crime by Nigerians in other countries. “The aim is obtain from other countries on reciprocal basis, mutual assistance in the prosecution of criminal matters including the location and identification of suspects, witnesses and other materials for prosecution of criminal matters,” he said. Other provisions of the law, he said, include the interception of telecommunications, conversion of electronic surveillance, restraint of dealings in property or the freezing of assets, that may be recovered, forfeited or confiscated in respect of offences. Buhari assents to Mutual Assistance in Criminal Matters Act 2019 The Senate, and Buhari’s anti-graft war Foundation for Buhari’s anti-graft war Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin